{"type":"message","id":"b8f7e2e1","parentId":"a66ac85a","timestamp":"2026-04-21T07:34:44.961Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still seeing \"already running under systemd\" spam from the latest restart attempt. The lock file was deleted, but there are still multiple processes starting. This seems to be an issue with the systemd service configuration where it starts multiple processes.\n\nLet me look at the systemd service file to understand what's happening. Also, looking at the log entries more carefully, I see entries at 07:34:08 and 07:34:18 which means the new process started but it's immediately seeing the old one as \"already running.\"\n\nWait - looking at the PIDs: the port is on 324512, but the old processes from before are still writing to the same log file. \n\nThe new process is actually PID 324512 based on the port binding, but the log shows entries from a different PID that appear to be from an older instance. The timestamps are sequential, so the issue is that multiple processes are still competing to write to the same log file even though the new one should be the active one.\n\nLooking at the process list, there are actually two openclaw-gateway processes running simultaneously - PID 324053 from the earlier start and PID 324512 from the most recent one. The older process is still hogging the port even though the newer one should have taken over.\n\nWait, but the port is showing LISTEN on 324512, which means the newer process grabbed it successfully. That suggests the old process might have released it somehow, even though systemd didn't actually restart it. The \"already running under systemd\" message is probably coming from the new process detecting that it itself was started by systemd and is now running. systemd; waiting 5000ms before retrying startup\"\n\nThis happens when:\n1. A new openclaw-gateway process starts via `systemctl start`\n2. It finds that another process is already listening on the port\n3. It exits immediately\n\nBut which process is already listening? The new process (PID 324512) might be the second one trying to start, and the first one (from a previous failed start) is still running.\n\nI'm realizing the problem might be timing-related. When `systemctl start` fires up a new process, it could briefly coexist with an orphaned process from a previous failed attempt before the service manager fully terminates the old one.\n\nThe real issue is that both processes are writing to the same log file, so when I tail the entries, I'm seeing a mix of output from both PIDs. The most recent entry at 07:34:18 shows the newer process detecting the older one still running on the port.\n\nLooking at the port binding itself, it shows LISTEN on 324512, but the log messages at 07:34:08 and 07:34:18 are coming from the older PID, which suggests that older process might still be holding the port despite appearing to have released it.\n\nI'm realizing the \"already running under systemd\" error could mean the current process itself was spawned by systemd and is detecting that it's already active. Let me check the systemd service configuration to see what the ExecStart command is actually doing—there might be a wrapper script or foreground flag misconfigured that's causing multiple processes to spawn.","thinkingSignature":"41f03e102dd038d5d4f408da14c55a879cd1b2a9e798b3ae7d1a2eac8f120013"},{"type":"text","text":"Check systemd service config:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uopqvlpzdbvt_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"expect -c '\nspawn ssh -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no root@161.248.81.140 \"cat /etc/systemd/system/openclaw-gateway.service\"\nexpect \"password:\"\nsend \"qOY)9Ym242jIv.\\r\"\nexpect eof\n' 2>&1 | grep -v \"^spawn\\|^Password\"","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":1385,"output":753,"cacheRead":51778,"cacheWrite":324,"totalTokens":54240,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"c