{"type":"message","id":"7697ccba","parentId":"a9699119","timestamp":"2026-04-21T07:35:12.066Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The systemd config looks fine. It's using `Type=simple` with just `/usr/bin/openclaw gateway --port 18789`. The issue might be the log rotation or the multiple attempts.\n\nLooking at the current state: port 18789 is LISTEN on PID 324512, and it's been stable for a while. The repeated \"already running under systemd\" messages in the log are from old instances that were trying to start and failing. The current instance (324512) seems to be running fine.\n\nLet me check if the gateway is actually healthy by checking if there are any recent log entries from PID 324512, and also check the systemctl status.\n\nActually, let me just check: the issue might be that my earlier `pkill` killed the processes, then `systemctl start` started a new one, but there was a race condition where the old log file still had entries from before the kill. Let me clear the log and restart cleanly one more time.\n\n\nThe systemctl service is configured with `Restart=always` and `RestartSec=10`, so it's continuously trying to restart. I think I see it now—there's a parent `openclaw` process spawning a child `openclaw-gateway` process, and the systemd service might be getting triggered multiple times, creating a cascade of restart attempts.\n\nBut wait, the service file only has one `ExecStart` directive, so there shouldn't be multiple restarts happening. Let me check the systemctl status to see what's actually going on with the currently running process.","thinkingSignature":"c0beded7adf755fce0ab5eb1f1f06f2f8e2d0cc4d61204b2368e10b117fcffad"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ykcy5w3pvr39_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"expect -c '\nspawn ssh -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no root@161.248.81.140 \"systemctl status openclaw-gateway | head -20\"\nexpect \"password:\"\nsend \"qOY)9Ym242jIv.\\r\"\nexpect eof\n' 2>&1 | grep -v